{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17500706","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17500706"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:16:25+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:16:25+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1662"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1662","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1662"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.56,0.18,0.02,0.2,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1662"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"50039"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1662","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1662"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1662"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35307"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1807"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7863"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8639"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13888"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"50039","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/50039"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 64-year-old farmer presents with persistent pain in his right foot. He spends most of the day on his feet. His medical history includes hypertension, hypercholesterolaemia and type 2 diabetes. On examination, his lower limb is of a normal temperature, with no discolouration or varicosities. His foot is warm, with areas of reduced sensation to light touch and pain. The dorsalis pedis pulse is regular. The ulcer is slightly tender to touch. His foot is shown below (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is most likely underlying cause of the ulcer?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Diabetic neuropathy","Peripheral arterial insufficiency","Trauma","Pressure sore","Venous insufficiency"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiabetic neuropathy\u003C/strong\u003E involves a combination of peripheral loss of sensation in limbs, particularly the feet and microangiopathy (occlusion of very small arteries) - predisposing patients to infection and non-healing of minor traumas which may go unnoticed and lead to ulceration. This patient displays sensory deficits in the lower limbs, suggesting the presence of diabetic neuropathy. This ulcer has well-demarcated, raised edges, and a yellow base suggesting deep erosion past the epidermal surface which are typical of diabetic foot ulcers. Whilst this patient has evidence of a peripheral neuropathy, it is not complete as he is still able to feel tenderness in the ulcerated area.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPressure sores\u003C/strong\u003E are macerated and surrounded by atrophic skin, as they caused by constant pressure on an area (often a bony prominence e.g. heel, sacrum) due to limited mobility. Although pressure may have contributed to this ulcer, the appearance, non-healing and depth of the ulcer suggests an underlying neuropathic cause. Here is an example (Image 1).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn acute\u003Cstrong\u003E trauma\u003C/strong\u003E is unlikely to cause an ulcer of this depth and appearance.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EArterial ulcers\u003C/strong\u003E are painful, well-demarcated, \u0027punched-out\u0027 lesions with a dark/necrotic base. Ischaemic pain at rest and presence over distal bony prominences are typical. He has no history to suggest peripheral arterial insufficiency (e.g. cool peripheries, intermittent claudication, smoking, cardiovascular disease). Here is an example of an ischaemic ulcer (Image 2)\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVenous ulcers\u003C/strong\u003E are shallow ulcers, with irregular margins and granulated or yellow fibrin bases. They are often found on the medial aspect of the calf and in the Gaiter area, rarely in the foot (Image 3). They are usually painless unless associated with infection. The history and clinical examination does not show any signs of venous insufficiency (e.g. previous DVT, haemosiderin staining, lower limb oedema, venous dermatitis).\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Venous Ulcers are typically found in the Gaiter area (lower one third of calf) are superficial and are usually painless unless associated with infection","Diabetic Ulcers are usually associated with pressure areas of the foot (bony prominences) and may extend deep to involve tendons and bone.","Arterial Ulcers are usually very painful (unresponsive to simple analgesia) with the features of ischaemic rest pain.  They are usually located distally in the foot over bony prominences."],"references":["Singer AJ, Tassiopoulos A, Kirsner RS. Evaluation and Management of Lower-Extremity Ulcers. The New England Journal of Medicine [Internet]. 2017 [cited 2023 Feb];377(16):1559\u201367. Available from: https://www.nejm.org/doi/pdf/10.1056%2FNEJMra1615243"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35307"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1662"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20024"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20640"},{"type":"media","id":"20943"},{"type":"media","id":"20944"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20024","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20024"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/8eaa6a20-0082-4062-8e7f-c4076268b8ed.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/8eaa6a20-0082-4062-8e7f-c4076268